              phenotypes, but also conserved expression programs underlying
              ancestral spermatogenic processes. Sex chromosome analyses show
              that genes predominantly expressed in spermatogonia (i.e., germ
              cells fueling spermatogenesis) and Sertoli cells (i.e., somatic
              supporting cells) independently accumulated on X chromosomes
              across mammals during evolution, presumably due to
              male-beneficial selective forces. Further work uncovered that the
              process of meiotic sex chromosome inactivation (MSCI) also occurs
              in monotremes and hence is common to the different mammalian sex
              chromosome systems, contrary to previous inferences. Thus, the
              general mechanism of meiotic silencing of unsynapsed chromatin
              (MSUC), which underlies MSCI, represents an ancestral mammalian
              feature. Together, our study illuminates the cellular and
